\newlabel{thm:s-entropy-compat}{{11.10}{27}{S-Entropy Forward Compatibility}{theorem.11.10}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {A reversal process $R$ has no available termination structure: its endpoint is a past state, unreachable by dynamic termination (Corollary~\ref {cor:no-repeat}) or controlled termination (which reduces to forward-time recurrence), with no third mechanism available (Theorem~\ref {thm:reversal-no-process}).} (\textbf  {A})~A forward process: $M(t)$ increases from $t_{\mathrm  {start}}$ (blue) to $t_{\mathrm  {end}}$ (orange). The endpoint lies in the process's future; forward dynamics determine when it is reached. This is the canonical structure of any process in Definition~\ref {def:process}. (\textbf  {B})~Putative reversal process $R$: $M_R(t)$ increases from $M = 100$ onward (forward time), but the target endpoint is the past state at $M = 30$ (dashed horizontal). The gap between $M_R(t)$ and the target grows monotonically; dynamic termination cannot reach the past endpoint, and the distance to target increases rather than decreases. (\textbf  {C})~Dynamic termination fails: each partition state along the forward trajectory is visited exactly once (Corollary~\ref {cor:no-repeat}). The state at $M = 40$ (orange marker) was consumed at step $40$ and cannot be revisited; a ``return'' to this state would require a second visit, which is structurally excluded by the bijection's injectivity. (\textbf  {D})~Controlled termination yields recurrence, not reversal: both the system's partition count $M_{\mathrm  {sys}}(t)$ (solid) and the controller's count $M_{\mathrm  {ctrl}}(t)$ (dashed) are strictly increasing. The controller uses memory of a past configuration to drive the system to a resembling configuration. Both agents run forward; the result is a forward-time memory-driven recurrence.}}{28}{figure.10}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:panel10_process_termination}{{10}{28}{\textbf {A reversal process $R$ has no available termination structure: its endpoint is a past state, unreachable by dynamic termination (Corollary~\ref {cor:no-repeat}) or controlled termination (which reduces to forward-time recurrence), with no third mechanism available (Theorem~\ref {thm:reversal-no-process}).} (\textbf {A})~A forward process: $M(t)$ increases from $t_{\mathrm {start}}$ (blue) to $t_{\mathrm {end}}$ (orange). The endpoint lies in the process's future; forward dynamics determine when it is reached. This is the canonical structure of any process in Definition~\ref {def:process}. (\textbf {B})~Putative reversal process $R$: $M_R(t)$ increases from $M = 100$ onward (forward time), but the target endpoint is the past state at $M = 30$ (dashed horizontal). The gap between $M_R(t)$ and the target grows monotonically; dynamic termination cannot reach the past endpoint, and the distance to target increases rather than decreases. (\textbf {C})~Dynamic termination fails: each partition state along the forward trajectory is visited exactly once (Corollary~\ref {cor:no-repeat}). The state at $M = 40$ (orange marker) was consumed at step $40$ and cannot be revisited; a ``return'' to this state would require a second visit, which is structurally excluded by the bijection's injectivity. (\textbf {D})~Controlled termination yields recurrence, not reversal: both the system's partition count $M_{\mathrm {sys}}(t)$ (solid) and the controller's count $M_{\mathrm {ctrl}}(t)$ (dashed) are strictly increasing. The controller uses memory of a past configuration to drive the system to a resembling configuration. Both agents run forward; the result is a forward-time memory-driven recurrence}{figure.10}{}}
